				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chubert" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(502908); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=502908&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610250856" alt="Chubert" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=502908)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/chubert" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(502908); return false;" >Chubert</a></span> <span class="odate time_1396209495 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">30 Mar 2014 19:58</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2001866">
									

<p>I am neutral voting this. The continual contemplation of suicide is not in itself a bad thing, it's just done too unsubtly to have an impact on me. The prose and writing are all right, if lacking some character, and the plot is okay. My biggest issue is the character development. In the last fifth of the story, everybody seems to take such drastic, unexplained changes in outlook that it's just too jarring for me to take seriously. The frog goes from being miserable and suicidal to being <em>happy?</em> Because it apologized? The bird who hated all humans and misled himself into thinking that the frogs were friends shows, like, no reaction? And understands what the humans did? It's deus ex machina characterization, wherein you develop your characters by way of sudden, conveniently timed epiphanies.</p>

							</div>

								
					
